    optionD: "Fidaxomicin provides long-lasting mucosal immunity against C. difficile spores, functioning as a vaccine",
    correctAnswer: "B",
    rationale: "FIDAXOMICIN is a macrocyclic antibiotic (not a macrolide) that inhibits bacterial RNA polymerase — specifically binding the sigma subunit, blocking the initiation of transcription. Its KEY advantage: NARROW SPECTRUM. Fidaxomicin has excellent activity against C. difficile (MIC₉₀ 0.25 μg/mL) but MINIMAL activity against normal colonic anaerobic flora (Bacteroides spp). WHY THIS MATTERS: The normal anaerobic microbiome provides COLONIZATION RESISTANCE — healthy anaerobic bacteria compete with C. difficile for nutrients and binding sites, produce secondary bile acids that inhibit C. difficile germination, and maintain short-chain fatty acid levels. Oral vancomycin, while effective at killing C. difficile, ALSO disrupts this protective microbiome → prolonged dysbiosis → increased C. difficile spore germination and recurrence (20-25% recurrence rate). Fidaxomicin preserves the microbiome → faster reconstitution of colonization resistance → lower recurrence rate (13-15%). For recurrent CDI: fidaxomicin pulse-taper regimen (EXTEND trial) or bezlotoxumab (anti-toxin B mAb, given with standard antibiotics).",
    explanationA: "The opposite is true. Fidaxomicin's advantage is its NARROW spectrum — it spares normal anaerobes that protect against C. difficile recurrence.",
    explanationB: "Correct. Sigma subunit RNA polymerase inhibition with narrow spectrum preserves anaerobic colonization resistance, reducing CDI recurrence compared to vancomycin's broader disruption.",
    explanationC: "Anti-toxin B antibody describes bezlotoxumab (Zinplava) — given as adjunct to prevent recurrence but not as primary treatment. Fidaxomicin is an antibiotic, not an antibody.",
    explanationD: "Fidaxomicin is an antibiotic, not a vaccine. It does not induce immune responses against C. difficile spores.",
    examTip: "CDI treatment by episode: 1st episode (non-severe): fidaxomicin preferred > oral vancomycin. 1st episode (severe/fulminant): oral vancomycin +/- IV metronidazole. 2nd recurrence: fidaxomicin pulse-taper or vancomycin taper. 3rd+ recurrence: consider fecal microbiota transplant (FMT) — 80-90% cure rate, or SER-109 (FDA-approved oral microbiome therapeutic).",
