    explanationC: "Ceftaroline does NOT affect the mecA gene or PBP2a production. PBP2a is still produced — ceftaroline simply BINDS it effectively despite its altered structure. The resistance mechanism is still present; the drug overcomes it through high-affinity binding.",
    explanationD: "Other cephalosporins CANNOT kill MRSA even at high doses — they physically cannot bind PBP2a's altered active site. This is a structural/affinity issue, not a dosing issue. Only ceftaroline/ceftobiprole have the required molecular configuration.",
    examTip: "Anti-MRSA agents by mechanism: Cell wall: vancomycin (D-Ala-D-Ala binding), ceftaroline (PBP2a binding), dalbavancin/oritavancin (lipoglycopeptides). Membrane: daptomycin (depolarization). Protein synthesis: linezolid (50S initiation complex), TMP-SMX (folate synthesis — technically DNA), tigecycline (30S). For MRSA BACTEREMIA specifically: vancomycin or daptomycin first-line. Ceftaroline for persistent bacteremia or vancomycin failure. Linezolid NOT recommended for bacteremia (bacteriostatic, inferior outcomes vs vancomycin in MRSA bloodstream infections).",
    category: "Pharmacology_Systems",
    subtopic: "Anti-MRSA cephalosporin pharmacology",
    difficulty: "hard",
