    rationale: "POLYMYXIN MECHANISM: Colistin (polymyxin E) and polymyxin B are cationic cyclic lipopeptide antibiotics with a DETERGENT-LIKE mechanism against Gram-negative bacteria: (1) ELECTROSTATIC BINDING: Polymyxins have 5 positively charged L-α,γ-diaminobutyric acid (Dab) residues → bind the negatively charged phosphate groups of LIPID A (the toxic, lipid component of LPS/endotoxin) in the outer membrane. (2) CATION DISPLACEMENT: This binding competitively displaces the divalent cations (Ca²⁺, Mg²⁺) that bridge adjacent LPS molecules → destabilizes the outer membrane's structural integrity. (3) MEMBRANE INSERTION: The fatty acid tail (6-methylheptanoic/octanoic acid) inserts into the hydrophobic core of the bilayer → further disruption. (4) PORE FORMATION AND LYSIS: Outer membrane becomes permeable → polymyxin accesses the inner (cytoplasmic) membrane → same process → loss of membrane integrity → leakage of cytoplasmic contents → RAPID bactericidal death. Additional mechanism: polymyxins bind and neutralize circulating LPS (endotoxin) → may reduce endotoxin-mediated sepsis inflammation (anti-endotoxin effect). HISTORICAL ABANDONMENT: Available since 1950s. Abandoned ~1970s-80s because: (1) NEPHROTOXICITY (incidence 20-60% with older formulations): Polymyxins are taken up by proximal tubular epithelial cells via megalin receptor → accumulate → direct tubular injury → acute tubular necrosis + decreased GFR. Usually reversible if caught early. (2) NEUROTOXICITY (7-10%): paresthesias, dizziness, confusion, neuromuscular blockade (rare respiratory paralysis — blocks presynaptic ACh release similar to aminoglycosides). RE-EMERGENCE: The WHO has declared antimicrobial resistance a top 10 global health threat. CRE (producing KPC, NDM, OXA-48 carbapenemases) are resistant to ALL beta-lactams including carbapenems → polymyxins often the ONLY active agent. mcr-1 plasmid-mediated colistin resistance is now an emerging threat to this last-line defense.",
