    optionC: "Avibactam works by directly killing bacteria independently of ceftazidime; it is a standalone antibiotic, not an enzyme inhibitor",
    optionD: "Avibactam is a diazabicyclooctane (DBO) — a NON-beta-lactam beta-lactamase inhibitor with a fundamentally different mechanism. Older inhibitors (clavulanate, tazobactam, sulbactam) are beta-lactam-based → form an IRREVERSIBLE acyl-enzyme complex with serine beta-lactamases → but are hydrolyzed (destroyed) by KPC carbapenemases before effective inhibition occurs. Avibactam forms a COVALENT BUT REVERSIBLE bond with the active-site serine → (1) it is NOT hydrolyzed by KPC → sustained enzyme inhibition, (2) after slow dissociation, avibactam is released INTACT and can rebind another enzyme molecule → 'recyclable' inhibitor. This covers Ambler Class A (KPC, CTX-M, SHV, TEM), Class C (AmpC), and some Class D (OXA-48) serine beta-lactamases. Does NOT cover Class B METALLO-beta-lactamases (NDM, VIM, IMP — these use Zn²⁺ instead of serine)",
    correctAnswer: "D",
    rationale: "BETA-LACTAMASE INHIBITOR EVOLUTION: (1) GENERATION 1 — Beta-lactam-based inhibitors: Clavulanic acid, tazobactam, sulbactam. Mechanism: contain a beta-lactam ring that acts as a SUICIDE SUBSTRATE → binds the active-site serine of beta-lactamases → forms an irreversible acyl-enzyme intermediate → enzyme is permanently inactivated. Spectrum: effective against Class A ESBLs (TEM, SHV, CTX-M) but NOT KPC (KPC's active site can hydrolyze these inhibitors before stable inactivation occurs) and NOT AmpC (Class C — steric hindrance prevents binding). (2) GENERATION 2 — Diazabicyclooctane (DBO) inhibitors: AVIBACTAM. Mechanism: forms a COVALENT CARBAMATE linkage with active-site serine → BUT this bond is REVERSIBLE (slow deacylation releases intact avibactam). WHY THIS MATTERS: (a) STABILITY: The carbamate bond is resistant to hydrolysis by KPC → sustained inhibition (KPC can hydrolyze the acyl-enzyme of older inhibitors, but cannot hydrolyze the carbamate of avibactam). (b) RECYCLABILITY: After slow dissociation (~2-hour half-life on enzyme), avibactam is released intact → can bind ANOTHER enzyme molecule → one avibactam molecule can inhibit MULTIPLE enzymes sequentially. (c) BROADER SPECTRUM: DBO structure fits Class A (KPC, ESBLs), Class C (AmpC), and some Class D (OXA-48) active sites. CRITICAL LIMITATION — CLASS B METALLO-BETA-LACTAMASES: NDM, VIM, IMP use Zn²⁺ (not serine) in their catalytic mechanism → avibactam's serine-targeted carbamate mechanism is irrelevant → NO inhibition. For NDM-producers: ceftazidime-avibactam is INEFFECTIVE → use cefiderocol, polymyxins, or aztreonam-avibactam combination (aztreonam is intrinsically stable to MBLs).",
    explanationA: "Avibactam is structurally and mechanistically DIFFERENT from clavulanate. Clavulanate is a beta-lactam suicide substrate forming an irreversible bond. Avibactam is a DBO forming a reversible carbamate — this chemical distinction is why it overcomes KPC.",
