    rationale: "RIPE THERAPY — FOUR DISTINCT MECHANISMS: (1) RIFAMPIN: Binds β-subunit of DNA-dependent RNA polymerase → physically blocks the RNA exit channel → inhibits transcription initiation → no mRNA, rRNA, or tRNA can be synthesized → bactericidal. Active against DIVIDING and SEMI-DORMANT bacilli (persistent organisms in caseous granulomas). Resistance: point mutations in rpoB gene (encodes β-subunit) → altered binding site → no rifampin binding. (2) ISONIAZID: PRODRUG → activated by KatG (catalase-peroxidase enzyme unique to mycobacteria) → generates isonicotinic acyl radical → covalently binds NADH → this INH-NADH adduct inhibits InhA (enoyl-ACP reductase) in the FAS-II pathway → blocks synthesis of MYCOLIC ACIDS (C60-C90 long-chain fatty acids that are the waxy backbone of the mycobacterial cell wall/mycmembrane). Without mycolic acids → cell wall integrity lost → bactericidal against actively dividing organisms. Resistance: mutations in katG (reduced activation) or inhA promoter (overproduction of InhA target). (3) PYRAZINAMIDE: Activated by pyrazinamidase → pyrazinoic acid → disrupts membrane energetics + inhibits FAS-I. Active in ACIDIC environment (within macrophage phagolysosomes). (4) ETHAMBUTOL: Inhibits arabinosyl transferase (EmbB) → blocks arabinogalactan synthesis (another cell wall component). RIFAMPIN CYP INDUCTION: Rifampin activates the pregnane X receptor (PXR, NR1I2) → transcriptional upregulation of CYP3A4, CYP2C9, CYP2C19, CYP1A2, UGT enzymes, AND P-glycoprotein. This is among the MOST potent enzyme induction effects of any drug. Affected medications: OCPs (contraceptive failure), warfarin (subtherapeutic INR), HIV protease inhibitors/NNRTIs, cyclosporine, methadone (withdrawal), azole antifungals, and dozens more. OCP interaction: ethinyl estradiol AUC reduced by 40-60% → breakthrough ovulation → pregnancy risk.",
