    rationale: "FOSFOMYCIN MECHANISM — EARLIEST CELL WALL TARGET: Peptidoglycan synthesis occurs in THREE sequential stages: (1) CYTOPLASMIC: UDP-NAG → MurA adds PEP → UDP-NAG-enolpyruvate → MurB reduces → UDP-NAM → sequential addition of amino acids (MurC-F) → UDP-NAM-pentapeptide → lipid carrier attachment. (2) MEMBRANE: Lipid I → Lipid II (addition of NAG by MurG) → translocated across membrane by flippase. (3) PERIPLASMIC: Transglycosylation (polymerization) and transpeptidation (crosslinking — PBP target of beta-lactams). Fosfomycin acts at STEP 1 of STAGE 1 — the absolute earliest committed step. It is a phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) ANALOG: structurally mimics PEP → enters MurA active site → its EPOXIDE ring reacts with the catalytic Cys115 residue → IRREVERSIBLE covalent inactivation → no UDP-NAM production → entire downstream pathway is starved of substrate → no peptidoglycan. WHY MDR ORGANISMS ARE SUSCEPTIBLE: (1) UNIQUE TARGET: MurA is not targeted by ANY other antibiotic → resistance mechanisms selected by beta-lactams, vancomycin, or any other cell wall agent do NOT confer cross-resistance to fosfomycin. MRSA, ESBL-producers, CRE, and VRE all retain MurA activity and fosfomycin uptake. (2) DUAL UPTAKE: Fosfomycin enters bacteria via GlpT (constitutive glycerol-3-phosphate transporter) AND UhpT (inducible hexose phosphate transporter). Resistance requires loss of BOTH transporters → fitness cost → rare in clinical isolates (though resistance can emerge during monotherapy for systemic infections — hence limited to UTI monotherapy). (3) SYNERGY POTENTIAL: Because it acts at the earliest step, fosfomycin synergizes with drugs acting at later steps (beta-lactams at transpeptidation, vancomycin at D-Ala-D-Ala) — sequential pathway inhibition. CLINICAL USE: Uncomplicated UTI (single 3g oral dose — achieves >128 μg/mL in urine for 24-48 hours). IV formulation available in Europe for systemic infections (used in combination for MRSA, CRE). NOT for complicated UTI/pyelonephritis as monotherapy (resistance can emerge).",
