    rationale: "FLUOROQUINOLONE TENDINOPATHY MECHANISM involves multiple pathways: (1) MITOCHONDRIAL TOPOISOMERASE II INHIBITION: Mammalian cells (including tenocytes) have topoisomerase II in mitochondria. Fluoroquinolones cross-react with this enzyme → mitochondrial DNA damage → impaired ATP production → tenocyte dysfunction and apoptosis. (2) DIVALENT CATION CHELATION: Fluoroquinolones chelate Mg²⁺, Fe²⁺, and Zn²⁺. In tendons, divalent cations are essential for collagen cross-linking (lysyl oxidase requires copper, collagen stability depends on Mg²⁺). Chelation weakens collagen fiber integrity. (3) MMP UPREGULATION: Fluoroquinolones increase expression and activity of matrix metalloproteinases (MMP-1, MMP-2, MMP-13) in tenocytes → increased collagen degradation → tendon weakening. (4) OXIDATIVE STRESS: Mitochondrial dysfunction → increased ROS → direct damage to collagen and tenocytes. The Achilles tendon is most vulnerable due to (a) poor blood supply relative to mechanical stress, (b) high type I collagen content. FDA BOXED WARNING: fluoroquinolones carry black box warnings for tendinitis/tendon rupture, peripheral neuropathy, CNS effects, exacerbation of myasthenia gravis, and aortic aneurysm/dissection. HIGH-RISK GROUPS: (1) Age >60 (44% of cases), (2) Concurrent corticosteroids (6× increased risk — corticosteroids also impair collagen synthesis), (3) Renal transplant recipients (immunosuppression + corticosteroids + renal clearance changes), (4) Renal impairment (drug accumulation), (5) Prior tendon disorders.",
    explanationA: "Fluoroquinolone tendinopathy is a DIRECT HOST TISSUE toxicity, not related to bacterial killing. Risk varies dramatically by population.",
    explanationB: "Correct. Multi-mechanism host toxicity: mitochondrial topoisomerase II inhibition, divalent cation chelation, MMP upregulation, oxidative stress. Highest risk: elderly, corticosteroids, renal impairment, transplant.",
